<h2 class="blog--title">
<a href="/blog/2017/02/23/spring-framework-5-0-m5-update">Spring Framework 5.0 M5 Update</a>
</h2>
<header class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item desktop-only">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon engineering"></div>
<a class="category" href="/blog/category/engineering">Engineering</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<img class="meta-data--icon" src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/4b12b9c0c665bc0345467c1a218ed0f7?s=20&amp;d=mm" />
<a class="author" href="/team/rstoyanchev">Rossen Stoyanchev</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2017-02-23 12:46:00.0">February 23, 2017</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="2850" href="/blog/2017/02/23/spring-framework-5-0-m5-update#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</header>
<section class="blog--post desktop-only">
<div><p>An update on the 5th and last milestone of Spring Framework 5.0…</p>
<h1><a href="#spring-mvc-and-spring-webflux" class="anchor" name="spring-mvc-and-spring-webflux"></a>Spring MVC and Spring WebFlux</h1>
<p></p>
<p>The name <em>Spring MVC</em> is both well known and widely used but it may surprise a few there is no actual project or independent distribution with that name. Rather it is a module within the Spring Framework distribution called <code>spring-webmvc</code>. Here is another trivia question. Did you know that the top-level package in the module does not feature “mvc”? Rather it is called <code>org.springframework.web.servlet</code>. Practically speaking those are details that we don’t have to remember. What matters is that we have a short and memorable name to refer to <em>Spring’s Servlet stack based</em> web framework.</p>
</div>
</section>
<a class="blog-preview--readmore desktop-only" href="/blog/2017/02/23/spring-framework-5-0-m5-update">
Read more...
</a>
</article>
